<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Foster's writes down UK assets by Pounds 459m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Foster's Brewing Group yesterday announced a 35 per cent write-down in the
value of its UK assets consisting of Courage, Britain's second largest
brewer, and a 50 per cent stake in Inntrepreneur Estates, a pub joint
venture with Grand Metropolitan.
The Australian group said the ADollars 955m (Pounds 459m) charge was
prompted by continued trading difficulties in the UK, a complex regulatory
environment, continental European brewers' increasing access to the UK
market, and rising take-home sales of lower-margin beers at the expense of
sales in pubs.
Analysts said the write-down brought the investments broadly in line with
book values of other brewers and with GrandMet's valuation of its half of
Inntrepreneur. GrandMet had previously written down its stake in several
stages while Foster's had maintained the book value.
The move, which Foster's announced with a 9 per cent fall in group profits
after tax and abnormal financial items for the year to June 30, was seen by
analysts as a prelude to further rationalisation at Courage and the
possibility of Foster's taking over a large part of Inntrepreneur. GrandMet
has previously indicated it would like to concentrate on its other food and
drink businesses.
Foster's wrote down its Courage brand names by ADollars 385m, goodwill by
ADollars 242m, Courage's fixed assets by ADollars 58m and its investment by
ADollars 270m.
But the Melbourne-based group also announced that it would offset much of
the balance sheet damage by writing up the value of its Australian assets,
and including a valuation for the Carlton and United brand names.
In its 1993 accounts, Foster's did not include a CUB brand valuation but
said, in a footnote, that directors considered them to be worth about
ADollars 1bn-ADollars 1.2bn.
Yesterday, Foster's said it had referred to an independent assessment when
deciding the value of the CUB brands but decided to pick a substantially
lower figure - ADollars 665m.
Foster's reported a 10.3 per cent increase in pre-tax profits at ADollars
308.4m. Sales fell from ADollars 6.49bn to ADollars 5.07bn, largely due to
asset sales. It said its three beer markets - Australia, the UK and Canada -
were still extremely competitive, and that volumes had declined slightly in
the UK and Australia. Canadian volumes were 'modestly higher'.
Operating earnings from CUB rose from ADollars 211m to ADollars 250m, with
market share climbing to 53 per cent. Pre-interest profits at Courage, by
contrast, fell from ADollars 208m to ADollars 174m, a decline exacerbated by
the strengthening Australian dollar. The contribution from Molson in Canada
fell from ADollars 107m to ADollars 78m.
Profits were helped by a drop in interest charges, from ADollars 343.3m to
ADollars 214.9m, with debt at June 30 put at ADollars 1.85bn, compared with
ADollars 2.64bn. Basic earnings per share were 8.7 cents, against 10.7
cents. The final dividend of 3.25 cents is unchanged.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
