<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Unions warn Blair on plan to modernise Labour
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The leaders of the two largest Labour-affiliated trade unions yesterday
warned Mr Tony Blair, the new Labour party leader, not to pursue his
modernisation strategy at their expense.
Mr Bill Morris, leader of the 950,000-strong TGWU general union, said the
'jury is still out' on the Blair leadership and described as 'a bit of an
insult' Mr Blair's recent description of the unions as a pressure group like
any other.
'We are more than a pressure group, we have a special constitutional link
with the party,' he said.
Mr John Edmonds, leader of the GMB general union, which has 830,000 members,
said: 'Tony has chosen not to speak in the traditional tones of the Labour
party, he does not use the time-honoured formulas. That gives rise to
anxieties.'
Mr Blair, who will not speak at the congress but will address TUC leaders at
a private dinner this evening, is expected to resist pressure to give public
support to striking rail signal staff.
But after the blood-letting at last year's Labour conference over the issue
of diluting union influence in party elections, neither the union leaders
nor Mr Blair want another row.
Mr David Blunkett, Labour party chairman, underlined in a speech to the TUC
congress yesterday that this should be a period of 'consolidation'.
He said: 'We have renewed our links, now it's time for consolidation and
continuity . . . we work in complementary avenues, side by side.'
Friends of Mr Blair said he was in 'full agreement' with Mr Blunkett on the
role of the unions in the modernised Labour party.
Substantial arguments over policy are not likely to arise until next year,
when a number of Labour policymaking commissions report. The unions will
want to hold on to the commitments made by the late John Smith at last
year's TUC congress for a substantial re-regulation of the labour market and
an economic policy emphasis on full employment.
Labour and the unions are likely to differ over the level of the minimum
wage, Labour's economic strategy and Mr Blair's plans for changes to the
shadow cabinet. The unions fear they will be marginalised in forming Labour
policy.
However, Mr John Monks, TUC general secretary, who shares Mr Blair's view
that greater distance is in the mutual interest of unions and party,
yesterday endorsed Mr Blair's union policy of 'fairness, not favours'.
Conference reports, Page 12
Observer, Page 21
</TEXT>
