<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Hopes for Swan Hunter rescue package collapse: Receivers
fail to agree going-concern sale with CMN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Prospects for a sale of troubled shipbuilder Swan Hunter to
Soffia/Constructions Mecaniques de Normandie collapsed yesterday after CMN
and receivers Price Waterhouse failed to agree a deal.
With the abandonment of negotiations for a going-concern sale to
French-owned CMN, 164-year-old Swan Hunter, one of the world's great
shipbuilding names, looks almost certain to close.
CMN, the only prospective bidder to emerge from a worldwide search by the
receivers, yesterday put forward proposals to acquire a section of the
Tyneside yard and intellectual property rights. It said this might enable it
to place a short-term design contract with Swans, postponing next Friday's
design-team redundancies.
After final talks in London ended in stalemate, joint receiver Mr Gordon
Horsfield said: 'The gap between us was too large to bridge and in these
circumstances no purpose could be served by continuing talks to sell the
business to Soffia/CMN.'
He said the receivers' next task was to discuss the implications with Swans'
remaining 660 employees. Price Waterhouse and union leaders will meet today.
Following the news of the failure of the sale, TUC general secretary Mr John
Monks last night wrote to Mr Malcolm Rifkind, defence secretary, urging him
to give the government's support to Swan Hunter's fight for survival.
With a deadline of Friday for the dismissal of Swans' design and technical
team - a move which would end the company's prospects of tendering for more
work - Price Waterhouse is urgently reviewing other approaches made by
potential buyers during the 15 months of receivership to see whether any
offers a last hope of a going-concern sale.
If that cannot be achieved, the company's physical assets on both banks of
the Tyne and its intellectual property will be sold off piecemeal in the
coming months. The last vessel on Swans' order book,the Type 23 frigate
Richmond, will be completed in November. Mr Allen Donnelly, the Tyne and
Wear Euro-MP, said: 'The whole sad series of events reflects the UK
government's determined efforts to take Swan Hunter out of the defence
procurement industry.'
In the latest of several proposals made in recent months, CMN had offered
Pounds 5m for the assets, against an estimated break-up value of Pounds
7.2m.
But price was not the only sticking point: the unions and the receiver were
unhappy at CMN's proposals for the workforce, which faced lay-offs without
pay. After more than a year of talks, CMN, which proposed setting up a shelf
company to acquire Swans, had still not provided financial guarantees to
underpin the transaction.
Mr Peter Chapman, one of the union leaders, said last night: 'We're
disappointed we haven't got a conclusion, but while we're still working on
the last frigate we still have some time.'
Shipwright Mr Harry Cooper said: 'We're destined to die, everybody thinks
that now.'
</TEXT>
