<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Four universities in project for Pounds 60m Docklands campus
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Four universities have joined the London Docklands Development Corporation
in a consortium to build a Pounds 60m university campus in east London's
disused Royal Albert Docks.
The group, which also includes London East Training and Enterprise Council
and the Labour-controlled Newham council, has made a formal bid for Pounds
10m from the government's new single regeneration budget, which brings
together the urban regeneration budgets of a number of government
departments.
This is, the consortium says, its first and 'potentially most critical'
request for funds. If built, the project would provide a big impetus to
government plans for a development corridor east of London. The corporation
has already committed Pounds 4.1m to the project and is in discussions with
the Treasury over raising further funds via the private finance initiative.
London First, the co-ordinating body for private-sector investment in
London, is supporting the project.
Up to 5,000 students would be catered for by the campus, which would be
owned jointly by the Queen Mary and Westfield College, the University of
East London, City University and London Guildhall University. A new science
and technology park would adjoin the campus. Up to 2,000 jobs would be
created.
The University of East London said it hoped to start admitting students to
the new campus in 1996 or 1997, when it is hoped the first phase of teaching
facilities will be ready.
Mr Bob Pringle, an executive director of the corporation, said: 'The
institute will specialise in industry-related applied science and
technology, attracting hi-tech, high-value industries which will change the
economic profile of this part of Docklands and aid the regeneration of the
east Thames corridor.'
Once completed, the campus will be funded by the Department for Education,
although it hopes to raise private sector income.
Picture, Page 14
</TEXT>
