<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Observer: Strike out
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The Clinton administration has carefully avoided getting sucked into the
rancorous negotiations over the three week old strike that has shut down big
league baseball in the US. But one administration official is really
fretting: William B. Gould IV, chairman of the National Labor Relations
Board.
A certified Boston Red Sox fanatic, Gould has contributed almost as many
paeans to the Sox on the sports pages as he has penned scholarly articles on
labour law.
Indeed, given his background he would would seem to be just the person to
sort out the strike before it spills over into the 1995 season.
However, the NLRB can only get involved in unfair labour practice complaints
and in unionisation ballots. Still, Gould can take some comfort from the
fact that when play stopped last month his beloved Red Sox attained second
to bottom place in their division.
Perhaps Gould would do well to write the season off.
</TEXT>
