<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / The British Association: Benefit cash claimants
'understated'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON, Science Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The number of people claiming welfare benefits is underestimated by at least
a third, according to a survey whose first results were released at the
British Association for the Advancement of Science meeting in Loughborough
yesterday.
The survey, funded by the Economic and Social Research Council, shows that
people are moving in and out of jobs, family relationships and welfare
programmes much more quickly than in the past - and more quickly than social
scientists had previously realised.
Far more people depend on benefits to top up their incomes in the course of
a year than claim at any given time.
The underestimate of the coverage of welfare benefits is most acute for
couples and single people of working age; for example the number of families
with children receiving income support is 64 per cent more than the figure
implied by the official counts of monthly claimants.
Single parents and pensioners, on the other hand, have less tendency to move
on and off benefits.
'What strikes me is how important the welfare state remains,' Professor
David Rose of Essex University's Centre on Social Change, a survey
organiser, said. More and more middle class people were realising that they
were 'just one monthly pay packet away from income support'.
The survey is based on a random selection of 5,000 households containing
14,000 people, who are interviewed every autumn about their social and
economic circumstances. It started in 1991 and will continue to track the
same group for many years.
The purpose is to discover the dynamics of changing lives - information that
is impossible to extract accurately from government statistics and from
large one-off 'snapshot' surveys.
Many people in the survey experience large fluctuations in income. Fifteen
per cent of individuals experienced a growth in family income of more than a
third between 1991 and 1992 and 13 per cent suffered a fall of more than a
third in the same period. So more than a quarter saw a substantial change in
living standards within one year.
Changes in family composition - children being born or leaving home, couples
forming or splitting up - were the most important reason for large changes
in income.
But changes in employment also played an important role, particularly for
women. The proportion of women moving backwards and forwards between
full-time, part-time, short-term and no employment at all within the course
of a year doubled from 10 per cent in the 1960s to 20 per cent at present.
'People are coping with a great deal of turbulence in their everyday lives,'
said Professor Jonathan Gershuny, director of the British Household Panel
Survey at the University of Essex.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
