<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / The British Association: Contraceptives research urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLIVE COOKSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
An urgent scientific programme to develop safe and effective new
contraceptives is needed to support other initiatives to limit the world
population, Dr Anne McLaren, president of the British Association, said
yesterday.
Speaking at the association meeting, which coincides with the international
population conference in Cairo, Dr McLaren said 'all the present approaches
were developed a long time ago and they all present problems, even for women
in developed countries.
'There are all sorts of new approaches now, which are not being fully
exploited today because there is not enough money for research,' she said.
Drug companies were doing 'very little' research and development in this
area, said Dr McLaren, a distinguished geneticist who recently chaired a
World Health Organisation scientific committee on new contraceptives.
'One can understand that because they are interested in recovering the costs
of very expensive R&amp;D and making profits - and they are not going to get all
that much money back from contraceptives designed for the Third World,' she
said.
Promising approaches, according to Dr McLaren, include contraceptive
vaccines which prevent the newly fertilised embryo implanting in the womb,
and male contraceptives which reduce sperm counts to zero without affecting
sexual desire or potency.
</TEXT>
