<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Credit card users make net repayment in July
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
British consumers repaid a significant proportion of their credit card debts
in July, after borrowing heavily on their cards in June, official figures
showed yesterday.
The Central Statistical Office said there had been a seasonally adjusted net
repayment of Pounds 35m on bank credit cards registered with the Visa and
Mastercard system in July.
This net repayment marked a significant reversal from June, when net
borrowing on credit cards had unexpectedly surged to a record level of
Pounds 267m.
This repayment also contributed to a significant fall in net consumer
borrowing in July, the CSO said.
Net lending to consumers through finance house agreements, non-mortgage
building society loans and bank credit cards operating under Mastercard and
Visa - a collective measure known as the 'narrower coverage' - fell to
Pounds 296m in July.
This was sharply lower than in June, when net lending had reached the record
level of Pounds 683m. The figure was also lower than the City had expected,
and some analysts yesterday warned that the drop might indicate a slight
fall in the level of consumer spending.
Mr Gerard Lyons, chief economist at brokers DKB, said: 'My feeling is that
tax increases are affecting the economy and there is a slowdown in consumer
spending. Today's figures are just the latest sign of this.'
The net level of non-mortgage building society loans also fell to Pounds 7m
last month, down from Pounds 24m in June. Meanwhile, net lending by finance
houses - a category which includes car loans and in-store retail loans -
fell to Pounds 324m, down from Pounds 392m in June, but higher than levels
seen in April and May.
Nevertheless, other analysts argued that the fall was distorted by a record
level of consumer borrowing in the previous month, and insisted that the
underlying trend remained relatively strong.
Measured on a three monthly basis - a figure which is a better guide to the
trend than the volatile monthly data - total consumer borrowing was Pounds
1.19bn in the three months to July. This was fractionally below the level of
lending in the three months to April, when consumers borrowed Pounds 1.28bn,
but well above the levels of lending seen at the same point last year.
Mr Chris Dillow, UK economist at Nomura, said: 'There is nothing in these
figures to suggest that consumer spending is slowing. Consumers are
borrowing as much now in nominal terms as they did in the 1980s boom.'
Measured in terms of new consumer lending, the data showed that the level of
new credit advanced in the month fell in all categories last month. New
lending on credit cards was Pounds 2.81bn, down from Pounds 2.99bn in June,
while new borrowing through finance houses was Pounds 1.86bn in July, down
from Pounds 1.95bn in June.
Measured in terms of the broad credit coverage - a measure which also
includes loans on all credit cards, personal accounts, non-bank credit
sources, insurance companies and retailers - the data showed that net
lending rose to Pounds 1.36bn in the three months to June, compared with
Pounds 872m in the three months to March.
</TEXT>
