<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Broadcasters discuss plans for digital TV
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The BBC, Channel 4 and ITV representatives are working on plans for digital
terrestrial television in the UK.
Exploratory meetings have been held between the broadcasting organisations,
and more are planned.
A key stage in the process, however, is to agree on a European standard for
digital terrestrial television.
The Digital Video Broadcasting project, which brings together 140
broadcasting organisations and manufacturers, has already produced standards
for digital satellite cable and is working on an agreed standard for digital
terrestrial TV.
The new system would have up to 16 new channels and would use digital rather
than existing analogue technology, but would be broadcast from normal land
transmitters.
The clearest hint that the BBC was interested in developing digital
terrestrial services came in July in the white paper on the future of the
corporation.
The document, taking its cue from the BBC, said the corporation intends to
start experimental digital terrestrial services next year.
It would hold talks with equipment manufacturers on the availability of
receivers and invest in equipment to produce programmes in wide-screen
format.
'It would aim to launch digital services, which could be received in
wide-screen or conventional format, by the autumn of 1997,' the white paper
said.
The BBC is conducting a feasibility study on digital terrestrial and will
take into account the plans of Britain's other broadcasters.
In July the government outlined its decision on the future of Channel 5 - a
compromise that set limits to the reach of a conventional Channel 5 in order
to retain enough frequencies for the eventual launch of digital services.
The existing broadcasters, including the operator of a Channel 5, would get
a digital channel to match each of their existing channels.
This would be for 'simulcasting' so that no one would be deprived of
service. Broadcasters such as the BBC hope they would also get additional
channels to launch new services.
Mr Stephen Castell, a communications consultant, says he intends to bid for
a Channel 5 licence to provide a digital multi-channel service.
Mr Castell is not backed by any of the large groups, which are planning to
operate a conventional analogue Channel 5. Instead he is promoting the idea
of 'owner-viewers' who would invest in his company, Channel 5 Digital
Television, and get a free receiver and discounted access to premium
channels.
</TEXT>
