<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Calor workers ballot on action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Workers at Calor Gas, the gas products company, are holding a strike ballot
over the introduction of personal contracts and pay cuts for some staff of
up to Pounds 100 a week.
The TGWU general union is balloting 370 drivers, filling-plant operators and
distribution workers at the company and an additional 50 drivers working for
Calor Transport, the contract transport division.
The dispute arose, the union said, when the management proposed earlier this
year to cancel the collective agreement for manual employees and replace it
with personal contracts. At about the same time, drivers in the transport
division were asked to accept a new agreement that would in effect cost them
between Pounds 90 and Pounds 100 a week in pay.
Calor said yesterday that the contracts and drivers' pay situations were
separate, but that the union had chosen to lump them together.
Mr Danny Bryan, national secretary for the TGWU commercial transport group,
said that the union had previously had good industrial relations with Calor.
'Many of the people here have long service records with the company and
can't understand why it is seeking to change things now,' he said.
Calor said that it wanted to put employees on a salaried footing. Mr David
McKinlay, communications manager, said: 'We are not wanting to derecognise
the union. All we want to do is talk about pay and conditions with the
individuals concerned.'
The union is opposing the new contracts because they will make pay rises
subject to personal assessments and introduce a new method of calculating
pay.
Mr McKinlay said nearly half the manual employees who had been offered
individual contracts had accepted them.
The pay reduction for drivers, he said, reflected a downturn in the road
haulage market. The result of the ballot is expected later this week.
</TEXT>
