<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Relaunch meets with general approval
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Union leaders yesterday congratulated themselves on a successful relaunch of
the TUC, although some dissenters complained about aspects of the internal
reforms and the change in style which has accompanied the move.
Mr John Monks, the TUC general secretary, who has pushed through the
relaunch, said it was about 'redirecting resources to where the action is,
that means to Brussels and to the shopfloor'.
The congress passed a composite motion broadly approving the relaunch, which
stressed concentrating resources in fewer areas, reorganising the TUC
committee system, and turning the TUC into a more effective lobbying
organisation.
However, Mr George Brumwell, general secretary of building union Ucatt,
implicitly criticised Mr Monks' attempt to turn the TUC into a
non-party-political lobbying organisation. 'It is futile lobbying in the
corridors of power,' he said.
There were also complaints about the smaller executive committee which now
convenes between the quarterly meetings of the TUC general council.
In addition, smaller unions believe some of the changes have been against
their interests.
Union officials say privately that the biggest test for the reforms will be
whether the organisation can cease being a remote London-based body and can
start to provide a useful service to local activists.
Mr John Edmonds, general secretary of the GMB general union, told congress
that some of the Pounds 8.5m spent annually on the TUC goes on servicing
local activists rather than union executives.
</TEXT>
