<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / CBI puts spotlight on late payers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The problems caused by late payment of bills are highlighted today with the
launch by the Confederation of British Industry's northern region of a
detailed survey, based on responses from 5,000 companies.
The survey, conducted with accountants Coopers &amp; Lybrand and Durham
University Business School, hopes to gauge the extent to which companies are
victims of late payment and how much they increase the problem by delaying
payment to their suppliers.
Mr Julian Kenyon, CBI assistant regional director, said the CBI hoped the
research would help to change the business culture on payment and ease the
cash flow difficulties.
The CBI estimates that nationally one in five companies risk going out of
business because of unpaid debts, which are said to total Pounds 145bn.
However, the CBI does not favour legislation, fearing it might result in
companies deferring payments until the last possible date.
The 5,000 companies include the top 250 by turnover in north-east England
and Cumbria. The rest are small and medium-size businesses employing under
500 people.
In tandem with the research, to be published in November, the CBI is
challenging northern businesses to sign up to its Prompt Payers Code, under
which companies pledge to adopt and stick to a clear, consistent policy on
paying bills.
</TEXT>
