<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / County review defies guidelines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Derbyshire's two-tier system of local government should stay intact, the
Local Government Commission announced yesterday, in defiance of the
government, which favours replacing two-tier counties and districts with
all-purpose unitary authorities.
While the commission recommends Derby becomes a separate all-purpose unitary
authority, it says the rest of Derbyshire, which is traditionally
Labour-dominated, should continue to be administered by a county council and
eight district councils.
It has withdrawn its earlier proposal to form a separate unitary authority
by merging the districts of Bolsover, Chesterfield and North East
Derbyshire.
Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary, rejected that proposal for the
county because he thought it possible to find a unitary solution for the
rest of the county.
The commission now favours creating just the Derby unitary authority. It
said: 'During the last nine months, support for a new unitary council in the
north-east of the county has eroded. At the same time, the county council
and five district councils have proposed ways to make the two-tier system
work more effectively.'
It said a unitary Derby would cost between Pounds 3m and Pounds 5m to set up
but was unsure of the effect on annual costs, which it believes could be
either Pounds 2m greater or Pounds 2m less as a result of the change.
The alternative of setting up a separate 'north-east Derbyshire' as well as
unitary Derby, which the commission described as 'viable', would cost
between Pounds 8m and Pounds 10m, with possible further annual costs of
Pounds 1m.
The Association of County Councils, which supports the new proposal, said
the commission had 'sent a clear signal to the government that it will not
be bullied into finding a unitary solution just for the sake of it'.
</TEXT>
