<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Walker squares up to theft charges
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr George Walker, the former chairman of the Brent Walker Group accused of
fraudulently inflating his company's profits, yesterday stepped into the
witness box at the Old Bailey to give evidence in his defence.
In two hours of questioning by his barrister, Mr Walker outlined his rise
from boxer to head of the property and leisure group.
He said he was the ideas man and deal-maker but trusted others to carry out
the detailed work of building up the company. Mr Walker and his former
finance director, Mr Wilfred Aquilina, are accused of fraudulently inflating
the profits of the Brent Walker group by Pounds 19.3m between 1984 and 1987.
The prosecution alleges this was achieved through bogus film deals which
enabled the company effectively to fund its own profits.
The markets were therefore given a much healthier picture of the company's
fortunes than was actually the case, it is alleged.
Mr Walker denies four charges of theft totalling Pounds 17m, two charges of
false accounting and one of conspiracy to falsify the Brent Walker accounts
to overstate profits. Mr Aquilina faces one charge of the theft of Pounds
4.5m, three of false accounting and one of conspiring to falsify accounts.
Questioned by Mr Colin Nicholls QC, Mr Walker explained how, from helping
run his wife's family garage in the late 1950s, he built up his business
empire.
Milestones in the development of the company included the 'Billy's Baked
Potato' fast-food chain in the 1960s, the development of the Brent Cross
shopping centre in the 1970s and the creation of the Brighton marina in the
1980s.
The expansion into film production with films such as The Stud and The Bitch
took place in the early 1980s, he told the court.
Asked if he was ever concerned with the accounting of the film division, Mr
Walker said his mental arithmetic might have been 'better than most', but he
lacked the necessary basic accountancy skills.
'I would not have the ability to do it,' he said.
The trial continues today.
</TEXT>
