<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Truce agreed in lecturers' dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS and RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Natfhe lecturers' union and the further education colleges have agreed a
truce in the long-running dispute over the introduction of new contracts and
conditions of service, John Authers and Richard Donkin write.
The union has been in dispute with the Colleges' Employers' Forum over the
contracts since colleges were removed from local authority control in April.
Local union branches in up to 120 colleges were due to hold strikes this
month over the contracts, which would involve halving lecturers' annual
holiday allowance.
College principals feared that strikes during this period would inflict
serious damage, as most course enrolments are handled in September.
Natfhe abandoned national negotiations in March after the appeal court ruled
that its ballot over national action was unlawful. But in a joint statement
Natfhe and the forum said they had agreed a formal schedule of negotiations
to last until the end of this month. This aims to reach 'a national
framework collective agreement that will embrace flexibility, productivity
and necessary contractual safeguards'.
While negotiations continue, the forum has recommended its members not to
introduce any new contracts, and the union has asked its branches to suspend
all industrial action.
Mr John Akker, Natfhe general secretary, said the statement followed
'intensive talks between the two sides'.
The joint statement added that 'substantial progress' had been made on the
length of the working week, the length of the working year, and workload
protection.
Mr Roger Ward, the forum's chief executive, said that about 40 per cent of
lecturers and about 90 per cent of college middle-managers had signed new
contracts.
</TEXT>
