<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / New Brazilian finance chief sticks to plan: Minister
promises continuing anti-inflation policy but stock and bond markets slip
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANGUS FOSTER and GRAHAM BOWLEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAO PAULO, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Brazilian government yesterday tried to assure domestic and
international observers that the country's latest anti-inflation plan
remained on course, despite the weekend resignation of Mr Rubens Ricupero as
finance minister.
Worries over the resignation and the possibility that it would affect the
presidential election chances of Mr Fernando Henrique Cardoso, the
government's candidate, led to the Sao Paulo stock market closing 10.5 per
cent down yesterday, from the Friday close, and to falls for Brazilian bonds
on international markets.
The new minister, Mr Ciro Gomes, met President Itamar Franco yesterday and
said the present anti-inflation plan - with its main component, a new
currency called the Real - would not be changed. Mr Gomes stressed that the
team of economists which has overseen the Real's introduction would stay at
the ministry.
Mr Gomes, the governor of Brazil's poor north-eastern state of Ceara until
his new appointment, said the resignation of Mr Ricupero was the result of
'lamentably bad luck'. The latter had quit after his private comments were
broadcast by mistake on satellite TV. He said he had no scruples about the
government using the anti-inflation plan to help its candidate in the
presidential election next month.
Advisers to Mr Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva, presidential candidate of the
left-wing Workers' Party and Mr Cardoso's main opponent, said they would
appeal to the electoral court, claiming unfair government support for Mr
Cardoso. Mr Orestes Quercia, another candidate, demanded that the court
disqualify Mr Cardoso. This is seen as very unlikely.
Mr Cardoso, who is leading in the latest opinion polls by 45 per cent to Mr
da Silva's 23 per cent, tried to brush off the incident. In an election
broadcast on Sunday night, he emphasised the Real plan, which has cut
monthly inflation from 50 per cent earlier this year to less than 5 per
cent.
The price of dollar-denominated Brady bonds - bank loans repackaged as
bonds, which form the largest part of the Brazilian bond market - yesterday
fell by more than two points before recovering slightly in later trade. The
US markets were closed for a holiday so most of the trade took place in
London, with some in Brazil and Argentina.
'The other main presidential candidate (Mr da Silva) is seen by investors as
more inflationary, and that is worrying the market,' said Miss Ingrid
Iversen, senior economist at Morgan Grenfell in London.
Feature, page 20
</TEXT>
