<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Cresson bound for Brussels: Commissioners nominated in
France and Germany
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN and MICHAEL LINDEMANN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France's new European commissioners are to be Mrs Edith Cresson, a former
Socialist premier, and Mr Yves-Thibault de Silguy, the top official in
charge of trade and European policy in the office of Mr Edouard Balladur,
the prime minister.
The contrasting couple starkly illustrate changing attitudes in Paris to the
European executive. France's outgoing Socialist president, Mr Francois
Mitterrand, has nominated an ex-premier. Mr Balladur, the Gaullist premier,
in naming a bureaucrat, has chosen to underline the new French conservative
desire to see commissioners as technocrats under the political thumb of
European Union ministers.
Mr Balladur yesterday invited Mr Jacques Santer, Luxembourg's premier and
Commission president-elect, to lunch to inform him of the nominations.
Sometime this autumn, Mr Santer will preside over a carving up of portfolios
among the new commissioners taking office next January.
The issue of precedence between France's two commissioners has been made
less acute by the Maastricht treaty which limits the number of Commission
vice-presidents to one or two, at the president's choice. In a college of
commissioners which, with Nordic and Austrian enlargement, could top 20, it
is not clear that either of the French appointees would make vice-president.
Mr de Silguy served in the Brussels office of French commissioner
Francois-Xavier Ortoli in the early 1980s, and spent 1990-93 with the
state-owned Usinor-Sacilor steel company. He is known to be interested in
the competition or external trade dossiers held by Mr Karel Van Miert of
Belgium and Sir Leon Brittan of the UK respectively. Some other
commissioners - and governments - will be wary, however, of seeing such
sensitive portfolios pass into French hands. Mr de Silguy played the key
role in orchestrating France's Gatt negotiations, and some of the toes he
trod on in Brussels remain bruised.
Mrs Cresson is most remembered in France for her unpopular stint as prime
minster in 1991-92, and abroad for her comments about the homosexual
tendencies of British men and of the ant-like characteristics of Japan's
workforce. But she remains close to Mr Mitterrand, whose desire to grant her
wish to go to Brussels posed Mr Balladur a problem of political imbalance
with his choice. In the end, Mr Balladur decided that the choice of Mr de
Silguy, who has also worked for Mr Jacques Chirac, would be impossible for
his presidential rival to oppose.
Mrs Monika Wulf-Mathies, leader of Germany's OTV public sector union, looks
set to become one of her country's two European commissioners after she was
proposed by the opposition Social Democratic party, writes Michael Lindemann
in Bonn.
Chancellor Helmut Kohl met Mrs Wulf-Mathies, 52, just as the SPD released
news of her nomination. Mr Dieter Vogel, the government spokesman, said Mr
Kohl respected Mrs Wulf-Mathies's 'ability and hard work', suggesting that
she has his backing. However, her formal nomination will depend on cabinet
approval.
The Free Democratic party, junior partner in the governing coalition, has
said it wants Mr Martin Bangemann, the present industry commissioner, to
remain in Brussels but much will depend on how well the party performs in
next month's general election.
All present commissioners, including Mr Peter Schmidhuber, the other German
one, end their five-year terms at the end of this year, although some will
be renominated. A new Commission formally begins work on January 7 but not
before the European parliament has approved all 17 members. For 12 years Mrs
Wulf-Mathies has lead the 1.9m-strong OTV and would be the first woman to
represent Germany on the Commission.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
