FT  06 SEP 94 / Hungary-Romania pact talks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VIRGINIA MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BUDAPEST
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Hungarian and Romanian foreign ministers said yesterday they would
restart negotiations for a much-delayed friendship treaty between
theirstates. The Romanian foreign minister, Mr Teodor Melescanu, who
yesterday became the most senior Romanian government figure to visit Hungary
officially since the end of communism in 1989, said he hoped the treaty
would be completed by May 1995. Previous negotiations broke down in August
1993 on border and ethnic minority issues. Mr Laszlo Kovacs, the Hungarian
foreign minister, said normalising relations with Romania was a priority of
Hungary's new government and that Budapest was prepared to state in the
treaty it had no territorial claims on Romania - Bucharest's key condition
for signing. In return, he hoped Romania would grant its ethnic minorities
human rights according to European norms. Romania's treatment of its
1.6m-strong ethnic Hungarian minority has been a frequent source of tension
between the two countries.
