<HEADLINE>
FT  06 SEP 94 / Airbus will run project to build military aircraft
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD GRAY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   FARNBOROUGH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Development and production of the Future Large Aircraft, Europe's proposed
military transport, will be managed by Airbus, the civil airliner
consortium, which announced plans to establish a new military equipment
subsidiary yesterday.
The move is designed to strengthen the FLA group and to help market the
aircraft to potential customers - including the Royal Air Force, which is
considering purchases of the FLA or the Hercules aircraft produced by
Lockheed of the US.
Announcing the move at the Farnborough International Air Show, Mr Dick
Evans, chief executive of British Aerospace, said Airbus had an excellent
record of managing aircraft development projects.
He used the occasion to promote the merits of the FLA against its American
challenger. 'The FLA is right operationally for the RAF. It is also right
economically, with lower life-cycle costs, and right industrially, as it
will protect 35,000 high-tech aerospace jobs in Europe. This is our only
opportunity for 35 years to become a part of a large transport aircraft
programme.'
The separate military subsidiary will include the Italian aerospace company,
Alenia, as well as the four Airbus partners, Deutsche Aerospace,
Aerospatiale, British Aerospace and Casa, of Spain.
The consortium estimates that there may be a market for 350 FLA in Europe
over the next 20 years. The intention is to provide customers with a
fixed-price, fixed-specification programme to reduce the risk of cost
overruns.
Exact shareholdings in the military subsidiary will depend on the financial
commitments from the companies involved and their respective governments,
and on the number of FLA each country requires.
The share-out of work will be determined by similar criteria. British
Aerospace hopes to make the wings for the new aircraft, while Italy and
Spain are competing for the final assembly line.
Shareholdings in the main Airbus Industrie consortium will not be affected
by the move. Mr Evans said the rapid consolidation of the US defence
industry posed challenges for European companies: 'Bringing FLA within the
Airbus consortium is one way of deepening ties between European companies.'
The FLA is competing with Lockheed's latest-generation C-130J Hercules to
replace the RAF's ageing transport fleet. Lockheed has valid export licences
for the UK, but it is under investigation in the US over alleged bribery,
Mr Evans said the FLA would carry more equipment further and faster than the
C-130J, at lower operating costs.
In a separate announcement, Lockheed said that refurbishing the existing RAF
Hercules fleet until the FLA became available in 2002 was not an option.
'Other Hercules fleet operators with newer aircraft have rejected the idea
of refurbishment,' said Mr Mickey Blackwell, president of Lockheed
Aeronautical Systems.
Air Show reports, Page 8
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
