<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: Emerging markets regain lost ground -
International
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Investors are slowly returning to the secondary market for emerging country
debt - one of the most volatile of all fixed income markets.
Earlier this year, amid turmoil in international bond markets, investors
dumped so-called 'Brady bonds' - paper issued to restructure medium-term
public sector debt to foreign commercial banks - and other emerging market
debt instruments.
The market remained in the doldrums for much of the spring and summer but
last month, following the stabilisation of US long bond rates and positive
political news in both Mexico and Brazil, prices began to recover. Analysts
and traders say the market could now regain more lost ground.
'The worst appears to be over. One big proviso is that US long-term interest
rates remain stable,' says Peter West, economic adviser to West Merchant
Bank in London.
West Merchant's secondary debt market index - based on the prices of 13
emerging countries' debt - shows a decline of some 25 per cent between the
end of last year and late April. More recently though, the index has
recovered, rising by nearly 9 per cent between July 25 and August 22.
Two factors in particular have helped. First, US Treasury bonds have
stabilised. Investors measure the yields of Brady and other traded debt
against that of the US long bond and the sharp decline in prices following
the rise in US short-term interest rates triggered this year's decline.
The more recent flat trend in long-term US rates - with yields around 7.5
per cent for some weeks - has helped confidence and has allowed investors to
focus more on a number of positive political developments in Latin America.
Second, the apparently 'clean' victory last month of Ernesto Zedillo, the
candidate of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party in Mexico's
presidential election, has reassured foreign investors in a country which
has issued a quarter of all Latin Brady bonds.
At the same time improving prospects for Brazil - which accounts for 37 per
cent of all Latin American Brady bonds issued - has had a big impact. The
fall in inflation following the introduction in July of the 'real' plan, has
helped Fernando Henrique Cardoso, the plan's architect and former finance
minister, surge ahead in the opinion polls, ahead of October's elections.
Mr West is particularly impressed by the commitment of Mr Cardoso to
thorough-going fiscal reform, which he believes could help consolidate the
country's recovery.
The rise in Brazilian 'Bradys' has led the rally, with the price of par
bonds rising by 10.9 per cent and C Bonds up by 22.3 per cent in the month
between July 25 and August 22.
There are some indications that the rally in prices has eased in the last
two weeks. In particular, Venezuelan debt prices have fallen sharply in the
last few days. Some analysts suggest that the good news on the Brazilian and
Mexican political scene has now been fully discounted in prices.
'We think that in the near term Mexican and Brazilian Brady bonds are
technically unlikely to rally from here,' says Mr Paul Luke, head of
emerging markets research at Morgan Grenfell. However in general there are
grounds for optimism about future prospects, Mr Luke and others point out.
Following this year's fall in prices, there is now a much greater difference
between the yields of different Brady bonds. The gap in 'spreads' between
the cheapest bonds, those issued by Nigeria, and the most expensive paper,
from Mexico, is now more than three times greater than it was eight months
ago.
'You don't have the spread compression,' says Mr Luke. 'Investors are being
paid more for taking the big risks.' In addition some Brady bonds, those
issued at a discount to face value and paying variable rates should benefit
from the rise in interest rates. Also despite the fall in prices, liquidity
has improved following growth in trading volume.
Trading volume in emerging market debt reached almost Dollars 2,000bn in
1993, more than twice the volume recorded in the previous year, according to
a survey by the Emerging Markets Traders Association.
The completion this year of Brady deals for both Brazil and Bulgaria and the
imminent prospect of an agreement for Poland has increased the supply of
paper. 'The market is basically broadening,' says Mr Rodzianko of Chemical
Bank in New York, who is chairman of the association.
Buyers have been coming back to the market, with some recovery of interest
among US institutional investors and mutual funds.
Mr Rodzianko says there has been growth in local interest, especially in
Brazil, where investment banks and other institutions have been active
recently. 'Brazil is going to be unstoppable. There is a high upside
potential,' he says.
Mr Luke is optimistic on prospects for Bulgaria and Poland and also says
Peru and Panama could be close to Brady deals. 'You need good fundamentals
or low prices or a combination of both. In many cases here you have good
fundamental stories where assets are cheap. You can't keep a good market
down.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
