<PROFILE>_AN-EIECYAEYFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940905
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: Frankfurt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER PARKES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Since last week's Bundesbank meeting provided no new clues as to future
German rates developments - the repo rate was again fixed at 4.85 per cent
for the next two securities repurchase offerings - the mood in the domestic
bond markets depends as usual this week on external influences.
For domestic investors, the DAX stock market index, driven entirely by hopes
of profits improvements, remains the focus of attention. Thursday's release
of first-half west German gross domestic product data has already been
widely forecast and discounted.
According to some dealers, the bond market is at present characterised by an
underlying negative sentiment, possibly exacerbated by post-holiday sloth
among dealers.
Last week's surprise rises in French banks' base rates prompted a flurry of
selling, sharpened by Germany's higher than expected industrial production
figures.
US labour market data for August, released on Friday, stirred a brief bout
of buying on the grounds that unchanged unemployment figures and lower than
expected new job signings signalled less buoyant economic activity. But bund
futures suffered later when US analysts claimed to have detected new grounds
for fearing inflation in a slight increase in hourly wages.
Today's US holiday will give German dealers a chance to make up their own
minds.
</TEXT>
