<DATE>940905
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: New York
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
US markets are closed today for the Labor Day holiday, but when investors
return to work tomorrow they are likely to still be digesting the
implications of last Friday's August employment news.
Although headline numbers were reassuring, the 30-year Treasury bond yield
rose to almost 7.5 per cent as investors were worried that the rise in the
manufacturing working week last month indicated a strengthening in the
industrial sector of the economy.
Friday's movement, however, seems overreaction to the data, and some rebound
in the market is likely tomorrow morning, particularly as there will be no
significant new statistics for several days.
The calendar is relatively quiet until Friday, with data on July wholesale
trade and consumer credit, second-quarter productivity and weekly money
supply growth unlikely to have any impact on prices.
Trading will be dominated by manoeuvring ahead of Friday's publication of
the August producer prices index. Broking house Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette
forecasts a 0.4 per cent increase in the August PPI, following July's 0.5
per cent rise, and a 0.2 per cent increase in the 'core' PPI, which excludes
food and energy. If the forecasts prove correct, the annual rate of producer
price inflation will be steady at 2.2 per cent.
</TEXT>
