<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: Tokyo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
While the government's view on the domestic economy will be released later
this week by the Economic Planning Agency's monthly report, bond prices seem
to have discounted a large part of the recovery.
The No 164 10-year benchmark bond closed up 5 basis points at 4.735 per cent
last week in spite of positive news over the government's financing.
Requests from ministries for the next business year have averaged increases
of 4.8 per cent, while the ministry of finance indicated only a 1.25 per
cent increase.
Moreover, the three-party coalition government announced that there will no
supplementary budget.
The steepening of the yield curve only seems to confirm that many market
participants expect a sharp jump in the economy, and a rise in inflation
rather than a modest recovery and subdued inflation figures predicted by
most analysts.
'The market is discounting recovery pretty far in advance,' says Mr Dick
Beason, economist at James Capel in Tokyo.
Meanwhile, news from the bilateral framework talks on trade with the US this
week may affect movements of the yen, which usually has a short-term impact
on bond yields. A stronger yen will support bonds, which are likely to face
profit-taking by institutional investors.
</TEXT>
