<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / World Bond Markets: London
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP COGGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Despite a busy week for economic statistics, the gilts market is likely to
focus on Wednesday's monthly meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, chancellor
of the exchequer and Mr Eddie George, governor of the Bank of England.
After hints that the Bank wants to see an interest rate rise over the next
few months, speculation will arise over whether the two men will immediately
move to push up rates from their current level of 5.25 per cent.
Ms Katy Peters, senior economist at Daiwa Europe, says most indicators have
shown little sign of inflationary pressure since the two last met. The rate
of narrow money growth is expected to slow, when announced on Monday; house
prices are weak; and annual growth of average earnings has stayed at 3.75
per cent. Ms Peters thinks rates will be left unchanged.
To help them decide on the strength of the recovery, industrial production
and manufacturing output figures for July will be released on Tuesday.
Analysts expect each of these to rise by 0.4 per cent month-on-month.
Whatever the economic and interest rate news, gilts may find it difficult to
make progress without the help of the international market. The yield spread
to 10-year German bunds fell below 140 basis points on Friday, having been
180 points a few weeks ago.
</TEXT>
