<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / EU delegates battle to head off abortion row: Dispute looms
at Cairo population conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX and MARK NICHOLSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAIRO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
European Union delegates launched a late effort yesterday to prevent bitter
differences about abortion overshadowing the International Conference on
Population and Development, which opens today in Cairo.
The EU wants to soften the language on abortion used in the draft statement
which has become the focus of angry opposition from religious conservatives.
The dispute over abortion has threatened to open up a new divide in
international politics, with Roman Catholic and Islamic states joining
forces to oppose more liberal proposals primarily from the US and some north
European states.
The talks to avert an open dispute came as more than 15,000 national
delegates, representatives of hundreds of non-governmental organisations and
about 2,000 journalists arrived in Cairo amid unprecedented security for the
week-long gathering.
The European initiative follows an EU agreement yesterday to a compromise on
abortion that could form the basis for a consensus among the 170 countries
at the conference.
The EU agreement bridged the conservative stance on abortion taken by
Ireland with more liberal proposals favoured by Denmark and the Netherlands.
Amendments to the draft document were being circulated in the corridors of
the conference last night by EU delegates. The central proposal was to state
in the document that 'in no case should abortion be promoted as a method of
family planning'.
However, the concerns of the more liberal western states are addressed by
the proposal to urge in the document that governments 'deal with abortion as
a major health concern'. The UN population fund estimates that 50m-60m
abortions are performed worldwide each year and that as many as 250,000
women die each year from poorly performed operations.
The compromise appeared to have won the backing of the powerful US
delegation, which has been the primary focus of criticism from the Vatican
and Islamic conservatives, who have accused Washington of endorsing
abortion.
Mr Timothy Wirth, US under-secretary for global affairs, said: 'The European
Union has come up with a draft language which we think is very promising as
a compromise.' He emphasised that the participants in the conference had
reached agreement on '92 per cent' of the proposed text during three years
of preparatory discussion.
Formal talks open in closed session tomorrow.
Cairo cobbles together a conference - at a price, Page 5
Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    EGZ  Egypt, Africa.
</CN>
