<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
We must be heading for Christmas: BBC2's autumn season starts today. Between
5.30 and 8.50 the network offers four new series and the first episode in a
complete re-run of The World At War, made at a cost of Pounds 1m by Thames
TV and first shown by ITV in 1973. It is a pity that Laurence Olivier, at
the best of times a bit of a ham, was so frustrated at not being seen that
he turned his reading of the commentary into a sequence of rococo sound
bites. Instead of being unnoticeable the narration is often horribly
intrusive. Otherwise these are exemplary programmes: 26 one-hour episodes
telling the story of the second world war (7.00). Italy Means Business is
the first of five programmes about how they do things in the land of Bugatti
and Gabrielli, starting at the odd time of 5.30. Murphy Brown is the pilot
episode of a hugely successful American comedy starring Candice Bergen as
the anchor woman of a television news programme (6.00). Fresh Prince Of Bel
Air is the fourth series of another American comedy (6.25). And White Heat
is the first in a series charting man's relationship with technology (8.00).
</TEXT>
