<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / This Week: Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALKARIM JIVANI, TV editor of Time Out
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
'She probably cried rape because the geezer didn't please her'. That's the
opinion of one juror in a rape trial. How do we know? Because Network First
(Tuesday, 10.40-11.40pm ITV) has come up with a hybrid documentary format
which allows the camera to be a fly on the jury room wall for the first
time. A group of actors devise characters for themselves and with the help
of police and the courts let us see what happens from the moment a rape
victim rings the police to the point where the lights are turned off in the
court. The police, barristers, judge and jury behave exactly as if they were
dealing with a real case and the entire proceedings are filmed with two
hand-held cameras and available light. This illuminates the process, without
the artificiality of reconstruction, in which one feels sorry for nervous
policemen stumbling over their lines. To what extent what we see is
artificial and how the presence of the cameras affect behaviour is debatable
but it is undoubtedly engrossing. The trial will be shown in three parts
(Wednesday, Thursday and Friday, 2.20pm, ITV) and an edited omnibus version,
next Tuesday evening.
Paranoia thrillers which play with power politics are very much the fashion
since the BBC's enormous success with the two Michael Dobbs serialisations -
House Of Cards and To Play the King. Faith (Wednesday and Thursday
9.00-10.00 and 10.40-11.40, ITV) a four - hour original screenplay is the
latest to come to the hustings and looks set for a landslide. Michael Gambon
is P J Moreton, a former minister about to return to office. But first he
must pay the political price by committing perjury. Customs and Excise is
after the DTI which had secretly sanctioned the sale of arms to African
guerrillas who are using them to shoot British aid workers. The scapegoat is
a small-time arms dealer who is waiting to be slaughtered at the Old Bailey.
Moreton also happens to be sleeping with his male researcher and there's
even a press baron with strangely antipodean vowels who has satellite TV
interests. The roman a clef element gives the piece its initial appeal but
the drama takes on its momentum, helped no end by a superb cast, including:
Susannah Harker, John Hannah, Keith Allen and Connie Booth.  The highlight
of the week.
The proms season comes to an end this week with the annual brouhaha which
may seem a modern aberration but in fact began in 1895 when Sir Henry Wood
ended the first Proms season with Koenig's Post Horn Gallop. The Last Night
Of The Proms (Saturday 7.45-9.00pm BBC2) has Wood's arrangement of Bach's
Toccata and Fugue in D Minor. Wood, who had been castigated for his other
arrangements, did not claim authorship of the Bach until it had been played
a few times and been well received. The fixtures of the last night, though,
are Land Of Hope and Glory and the Hornpipe. The latter was introduced to
mark the centenary of the Battle of Trafalgar and the promenaders tried to
outdo the orchestra by tapping their feet faster and faster. That
boisterousness has now become the distinguishing factor of the evening. So
much so that Sir Malcolm Sargent once had to appeal to the audience not to
throw 'streamers of excessive width'. He meant toilet rolls.
</TEXT>
<XX>
