<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / This Week: Music
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER ASPDEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
There is little doubt that the cult sound of the autumn will be Jan
Garbarek's collaboration with The Hilliard Ensemble, Officium (ECM New
Series), released today. Garbarek, the Norwegian saxophonist, has added his
instrumental skills to a collection of ancient chants, some of which date
back to the 12th century. The result is a curiously compatible blend, which
certainly meets the current demand for spirituality in music - expect the
Gregorians to be knocked off the top of the classical charts.
After a seven-year break, Bryan Ferry (below) has brought out Mamouna
(Virgin), a new album of original songs, with the unlikely aid of some old
friends - Phil Manzanera, Andy Mackay and even Brian Eno, who co-wrote
'Wildcat Days'. Plus ca change. The narcissistic Ferry, as ever surrounding
himself with glamour, still pays too much attention to slick production
values at the expense of his song-writing. The album marks the beginning of
a world tour, with four British dates in October.
The Three Tenors are not the only ones cashing in on post-World Cup fever;
the first in what is bound to be a rush of compilations of Brazilian music
is Brazilica], Talkin' Loud's collection of samba and bossa nova, featuring
seminal names such as Sergio Mendes, Milton Nascimento and Gilberto Gil.
Best to play on a wet February evening while practising one-touch back-heels
in the sitting room.
In brief: Nicholas McGegan conducts the Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra and
the choir of Clare College, Cambridge for a bright, crisp performance of
Purcell's Dido and Aeneas (harmonia mundi). Riccardo Muti and the Orchestra
Filarmonica della Scala combine Elgar's In the South (Alassio) overture with
Brahms's youthful Serenade No. 1 in D major (Sony). The Ensemble Musique
Oblique with Rachel Yakar and Isabelle Veyrier tackle a selection of works
by the Belgian composer Guillaume Lekeu, who died in 1894 just one day after
his 24th birthday (harmonia mundi).
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
