<PROFILE>_AN-EIECYACAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>940905
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Sport: Actions speak louder . . .
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA THOMPSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Last month the finest sprint filly in Britain, Lochsong, finished last at
York, in a race she was odds-on favourite to win. Her distraught connections
blamed her performance on the fact that, before the race, she had been
obliged to take part in a parade, at which her febrile temperament had
protested. She had twisted and yearned away from her jockey, and nearly
injured herself in the process. She had galloped to the stalls with
terrified ferocity and, all in all, she had exhausted herself before the
race had even begun.
This had happened to Lochsong before, and exemption from the parade had
therefore been requested for the York race. Afterwards, the authorities
conceded that in future such a request would be considered more favourably.
They did, however, make at the same time a defence of the parade, which was
that it allows the whole of the race-going public full view of the horses
and, as such, plays a part in race procedure.
More precisely, what it does is to create a spectacle, by presenting the
competitors to their audience. It gives them to us, the watching world,
rather than leaving them within their own sphere - that of the sport in
which they are competing.
I thought of Lochsong and her reluctance to parade for us when I read, last
week, that Ellery Hanley had been appointed the new coach of the Great
Britain rugby league team. Hanley has been the greatest player of his
generation but he has, throughout the years of his supremacy, refused any
dealings with the media. He has captained Wigan and Great Britain to several
notable successes and then, at the end of the match, as the reporters began
to cluster for their quotes, he has mysteriously evaporated.
Apparently this is not the thing to do. The consensus within the media - and
possibly outside of it - is that a captain's duties do not end when the
match is over. He has thereafter to explain, to sell the game, to give it to
its audience, despite the fact that they have just had it; in refusing to do
all this, Hanley was dodging his responsibilities.
Yes, he could rouse his team to glorious heights, but that was not good
enough if he would not tell us how he had done it, if he would not share it
with us.
This demand that sportsmen be talkers, as well as players, is inspired by
the same principle that expects horses to be show animals as well as racers.
One can understand this principle, but it isn't, ultimately, all that
sensible. For example, it demands that Lochsong take part in a parade,
despite the fact that, if she does so she will no longer be the great horse
that the public wants to see on parade.
Surely it would be better to see her simply run to her full abilities?
Therein lies her true self, just as Ellery Hanley's lies on the pitch and
not behind a microphone.
Yet the notion persists that sporting personalities must, come what may,
give themselves to their public, off, as well as on, their fields of combat.
No matter that Lochsong's nerves cannot cope with it, nor that Hanley had
experiences with the press that made him not want to cope with it. Their
sporting excellence is not enough. We must have the whole of them - or what
passes for the whole of them.
It has even been suggested that Lochsong - Lochsong, with her magical turn
of foot] - is a flawed horse because of her delicate temperament. Certainly
it was suggested that Hanley's extreme taciturnity would preclude his
appointment as Great Britain team coach.
With regard to this, it might be easier to understand the demand that
sportsmen speak to us, give to us, if they were saying or giving anything of
value; but the way in which most interviews are conducted makes that
unlikely. Some 99 per cent of them have no point. The truth is that
interviewing sportsmen is ridiculously hard. What they do is supremely
defiant of analysis; their genius is instinctive, surprising and momentary,
and they themselves are scarcely in a position to understand it. It would
take an interviewer as persistent and sensitive as John Freeman to unearth
their emotions and motivations with any degree of success. But no such luck
 -we must have instead 'how did you feel after scoring that goal?'
(terrible); 'how disappointed are you about losing that race?' (not at all,
I'm delighted); and 'did you enjoy performing in front of your home crowd?'
(no, I'd rather be in Papua New Guinea). Are we really losing something so
precious if a sportsman refuses to answer such questions?
I know that the media helps to create a celebrity and that, in return, the
celebrity should help to create the media. But the fact is that some of them
do it better than others, and it is hard to see why sporting personalities
who prefer to let their actions speak, or parade, for them should be forced
to do otherwise.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
