<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Bankers take a hard look at Ucatt account
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Among the concerns of trade union leaders this week will be Ucatt, the
construction union which has been living beyond its means for years.
Financial observers say that if it had been a private company it would have
gone into liquidation long ago. The union has been struggling all year to
sort out its finances amid persistent but erroneous rumours that it was
bankrupt.
In July the union reported it was spending Pounds 10,000 over its Pounds
1.4m overdraft facility with Unity Trust Bank, which is closely monitoring
its cashflow on a monthly basis. The Pounds 48,000 of monthly union staff
salaries were as much as the size of its bank charges.
An internal report earlier this year by the union's accountants HW Fisher
argued bluntly that Ucatt's structure was large enough to cover a membership
of more than 250,000 while the total was down to 135,000 with only 74,000
paying full subscriptions.
It suggested the union should consider whether it needed any regional
offices at all, and be concerned at the 'low level of paying members' as
well as their recruitment into membership. Ucatt forecast a 10 per cent drop
in membership level this year.
The original rescue plan for Ucatt proposed savings of Pounds 600,000 from
staff redundancies, the sale of Pounds 650,000 of union properties and
increasing membership subscriptions in 1995 generating an extra Pounds
240,000 inflow.
The bank's own accountants, KPMG Peat Marwick, also carried out a study of
Ucatt's finances that suggested the measures proposed in the original rescue
plan would 'not lead to the union generating net positive cashflows until
1995'.
The report warned that Ucatt's business plan would mean its borrowing would
need to exceed its existing financial facilities with the bank by as much as
Pounds 800,000.
It said: 'During this period the security available to the bank diminishes.
If the cash contingencies are included in the forecasts the deficit between
borrowings, facility and available security are exacerbated.'
KPMG concluded that: 'Unity Trust Bank is being asked to significantly
increase its exposure to political loss. Viewed from a purely commercial
perspective there is a very strong argument for the bank declining to
provide any additional facility over and above that currently available. If
such a decision were taken the ability of the union to continue in its
current form is very doubtful.'
The report recommended that a Pounds 200,000 cash contingency would have to
be built into the union's assumptions both this year and next 'in view of
the various uncertainties surrounding the achievement of the surplus'.
A Ucatt spokesman said yesterday that the union was working effectively to
repair its financial position.
Yet the saving of Ucatt may well depend on a rapid takeover of its
engagements by the TGWU, which itself has gone through a radical
restructuring with the help of the bank.
</TEXT>
