<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Revenue plan on personal files sparks alarm
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Inland Revenue plans to merge its five computer systems and allow more
of its staff to gain access to taxpayers' personal records. The moves have
sparked concern among civil liberties campaigners.
The Revenue is also going to give additional details to the Department of
Social Security about employers who are potentially liable for National
Insurance contributions.
The changes to computer systems come as part of the Revenue's 'change
management' programme, which includes ambitious modernisation of its
computer systems and greater responsiveness to taxpayer demands.
Staff at Revenue tax inquiry offices throughout the country - and others who
answer taxpayer telephone inquiries - will for the first time be able to
gain access to all personal tax information.
The move, which the Revenue says comes in response to a desire from the
public for easier access and quicker resolution of queries, will add to the
number of tax officials able to gain access to personal financial
information.
The Revenue stresses that the officials able to view the information will be
those who already hold sufficiently senior positions to be permitted to
inspect taxpayer returns.
It points out that most of the additional staff able to see taxpayer records
will not be able to amend them, and that details of those inspecting the
information will be logged.
Separately, the Revenue has announced that it will provide the Department of
Social Security with the names and addresses of employers likely to be
liable for payment of Class 1A National Insurance contributions on company
cars and fuel.
Sir George Young, the financial secretary to the Treasury, has approved
changes in the Revenue's powers which will allow it to supply the
information without breaching its confidentiality obligations.
Mr John Wadham, legal director of Liberty, formerly the National Council for
Civil Liberties, said yesterday that he was concerned about the plans.
'There is a problem with more people getting access to records,' he said.
He said that taxpayers should be able to have complete access to any
information in their records held by the Revenue, and stressed the
importance of a system that would log the names of officials who inspected
these records.
He questioned whether it was right for information collected by the Revenue
for one purpose to be allowed to be passed on to another department for a
different purpose.
</TEXT>
