FT  05 SEP 94 / Spending urged to cut crime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The enormous financial costs of crime make a convincing case for more
investment in its prevention, says the national crime prevention
organisation Crime Concern in a report today.
It says that although crime is a significant drain on individual, public and
corporate resources, little information is available about its impact in a
number of economic sectors.
The report says the full cost of crime is difficult to quantify since much
of it is not reported to the police.
A CBI/Crime Concern working party estimated the loss to business from crime
to be between Pounds 5bn and Pounds 10bn a year.
