<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / IoD warns on interest rate increase
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A warning that higher interest rates will damage economic growth was sounded
by the Institute of Directors yesterday in advance of Wednesday's monthly
economic meeting between Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, and Mr Eddie
George, governor of the Bank of England.
Mr Tim Melville-Ross, the director-general of the institute, said that its
bi-monthly business opinion survey revealed continued uncertainty among
members although the economy was growing quite strongly.
He said: 'With inflation at such low levels, there is no case at present for
a damaging increase in interest rates.'
Summer speculation about an early interest rate rise abated after the
announcement of a fall in the underlying rate of inflation from 2.4 per cent
in June to 2.2 per cent in July.
Although the Bank of England has warned that the government's targets for
reducing underlying inflation would be at risk without a base rate increase
in the next few months, analysts do not expect this week's meeting to lead
to an immediate change.
Mr Melville-Ross said there were few signs of higher inflation in the
pipeline and if exports, rather than consumer spending, continued to provide
the impetus for economic growth 'it could be next year before the situation
warrants a base rate rise'.
The survey found 76 per cent of directors saying that their companies were
doing well or very well. This was down slightly from 79 per cent in June.
There were falls in the proportion reporting improved volume and profit.
These were from 70 per cent in June to 63 per cent in August for volume, and
from 62 per cent to 54 per cent for profit.
The share of respondents feeling more optimistic about the economy nudged up
from 44 per cent to 46 per cent.
Signs of economic growth were given as the main cause of optimism, while
political uncertainty was the biggest inhibiting factor.
The Finance &amp; Leasing Association says heavy discounting in the summer sales
produced a slackening of consumer credit in July.
The association says in its monthly consumer credit and business finance
report that although consumers used credit in the sales, it was to buy
heavily discounted items.
As a result, consumer credit of Pounds 1.276bn in July was 7 per cent down
from June. Although the association's July figure represents a 28 per cent
year-on-year increase it was the lowest annual rise since October.
</TEXT>
