<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Growth forecast in airport retailing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Retail sales at UK airports are expected to total Pounds 600m this year  -
50 per cent more than in 1990 - making airports one of the fastest-growing
retailing sectors, says a report by Corporate Intelligence, the retail
research group, Neil Buckley writes.
The report says that airport retailing has grown at three times the rate of
high-street sales. Seven airports owned by BAA, the privatised airport
authority, account for 80 per cent of the total, and BAA makes more from
retailing than from aircraft landing charges.
However, 60 other UK airports have scheduled services, indicating the huge
growth potential for airport retailing. The report says that the large
number of passengers passing through airports, who are 'captive' and often
in holiday mood, means shops at Heathrow and Gatwick enjoy annual average
sales densities of more than Pounds 1,500 per sq ft - three or four times
the average for high-street shops.
Several retailers, including Bally and Laura Ashley, enjoy their highest
sales per square foot of any UK outlets in their airport stores.
The report says that well-known names such as Harrods and Hamleys have
opened airport outlets, while many niche retailers are basing their
expansion strategies around airports.
Airport Retailing in the UK. Corporate Intelligence, 51 Doughty Street,
London WC1N 2LS. 071-696 9006. Pounds 195
Business Travel, Page 10
