<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Call to reform market franchises
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The National Association of British Market Authorities is expected to call
for the government to put forward new plans to reform market franchise
rights at its annual conference in Llandudno, north Wales, today.
The association, a group of 135 local authorities, is proposing a system of
local authority registration or licensing of all commercial markets,
including car boot sales.
It will today debate a resolution recognising the need for market franchise
rights to be reviewed and calling for the Department of the Environment to
start consultations for new legislation. The group spearheaded the
successful campaign to persuade the government to withdraw clauses in its
deregulation bill abolishing the existing market franchise rights. Under
centuries-old laws these allow many local authorities to control street
market trading.
The association joined forces earlier this year with eight other
organisations, including the Association of British Chambers of Commerce,
the Federation of Small Businesses and the National Market Traders'
Federation to form an umbrella group, the Campaign for Quality Markets.
Campaign members say abolishing the ancient rights would lead to an
explosion of car boot sales and unauthorised markets.
The government says the rules are anachronistic and are misused by some
councils to stifle business initiatives.
The association says, however, that the government has failed in its pledge
to bring forward proposals to reform market franchise rights, which the
association admits contain many anomalies and need updating.
It is worried that the government will try to reintroduce clauses abolishing
the rights into the deregulation bill when it continues its passage through
parliament.
Mr Brian Ormshaw, secretary of the association, said it was ready to rally
cross-party support for its campaign in the autumn. 'The present law needs
to be reviewed but market franchise rights are crucial in protecting the
health of town centres and in preventing crime - both objectives which are
supposed to be dear to the government's heart.'
</TEXT>
