<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Writ names Saunders as marketing adviser
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Ernest Saunders is back in business as a marketing consultant.
Just over three years after the former Guinness chief executive was released
on parole for his part in the Guinness affair, having told a Court of Appeal
that he was suffering from pre-senile dementia, resembling Alzheimer's
disease, he has been named on a writ as marketing adviser to a troubled
publishing venture.
He is being sued in a legal battle between the two partners in a joint
venture called Retail Revolution, which planned to launch 30 magazines to be
sold exclusively through petrol stations.
Retail Revolution was set up by Mr David Elias, the multi-millionaire owner
of Harpur, a finance group, and Mr Richard Desmond, chairman of Northern and
Shell, which owns a range of magazines including Penthouse.
Mr Saunders is named as one of nine defendants in a writ issued by Mr
Desmond's company, St Alban's Investments. The former Guinness executive was
hired by Mr Elias as a marketing consultant for the venture. The other
defendants include Mr Elias and his company, the Richbell Group.
The writ, issued by St Alban's last month, alleges that it was excluded from
the management of the affairs of the joint venture and that money was spent
on the venture without its authority. The total damages sought are thought
to total about Pounds 1.39m.
Mr Elias responded a few days later by issuing a writ against Mr Desmond and
Northern and Shell claiming breaches of the joint venture agreement.
Retail Revolution had planned to publish 30 magazines this month - the
largest number of titles ever launched by a single publisher in the UK.
The planned titles, to have been produced by Northern and Shell, included
Bodytalk, a health magazine, Megaboobs, an adult magazine and Brainbox, a
puzzle publication.
The venture aimed to sell the magazines through 4,500 petrol stations rather
than traditional newsagents to achieve substantial savings in distribution
costs. Harpur has a relationship with these stations as a supplier of fuel
credit cards.
Retail Revolution is still technically in operation as a company but
Northern and Shell has terminated its involvement in the venture and refused
to resume its supply of magazines.
