<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Adams preaches to the unconverted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
In Northern Ireland megaphone diplomacy has often been blamed for
exacerbating tensions between the two communities. Mr Gerry Adams, president
of Sinn Fein, the political wing of the IRA, yesterday took the art one step
further to try to reassure unionists that they have a role to play in the
peace process,
Speaking to a crowd of republican sympathisers at a rally on Belfast's
predominantly Roman Catholic Falls Road, Mr Adams said he was turning up the
loudspeakers so 'our people on the Shankill can hear'.
Of all the groups mulling over the implications of last week's IRA
'cessation of military operations' the reaction of the people of the
Shankill Road and other so-called 'loyalist' strongholds is vital if a
political settlement is to be found.
In Protestant ghettos such as Blackstaff, where unemployment is as high as
80 per cent according to local community leaders, there is deep scepticism.
There is also a resentment that the republicans have not so much seized the
opportunity for peace, but won a public relations victory.
One man said: 'Why do the republicans have to be so cocky, marching in front
of the RUC barracks and writing 'go home' on the wall. This isn't Berlin.'
On the first Sunday after the ceasefire the churchgoing community was
striving for a reconciliation.
Catholics gathering in St Peter's Church near the infamous Divis Flats, one
of the most blighted inner-city areas, heard Monsignor Thomas Toner warn
that peace is 'not just the cessation of military operations. Peace is a
process that only begins with the cessation of military operations'.
Before the service he said: 'It's not going to be the catwalk that some
people think it is. But if the peace brings jobs there can be a real
regeneration. If those hopes are dashed there can be an awful depression.'
Last night, amid renewed speculation that the Ulster Volunteer Force, the
largest of the loyalist paramilitary organisations, may also be preparing
for a ceasefire the mood in the city was one of expectation.
Mr Tom Hartley, Sinn Fein general secretary, said as the rally rounded
Springfield Road, site of numerous killings: 'There's uncertainty for them,
but there's uncertainty for us too.'
One Catholic pointed to people waving the Irish flag in front of a police
station, a sight which a few years ago would have prompted a security
clampdown. He said: 'People sometimes forget what the tricolour actually
means. The green is for the republicans, the orange is the Protestants and
the white is the open ground between us. We're not going to ram anything
down their throats, but we're not going backwards, everything's changed
now.'
</TEXT>
