<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Crime prevention investment urged
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The enormous financial costs of crime make a convincing case for more
investment in its prevention, says the national crime prevention
organisation Crime Concern in a report today.
Crime Concern points out that although crime was a significant drain on
individual, public and corporate resources, little information was available
about its impact in a number of economic sectors.
The report was commissioned by the Thames Valley Partnership, which was set
up last year to achieve a united approach to tackling crime in Berkshire,
Buckinghamshire and Oxfordshire.
It says the full cost of crime is difficult to quantify because much of it
is not reported to the police. But running the criminal justice system cost
Pounds 9bn in 1991-92, while a CBI/Crime Concern working party estimated the
loss to business to be between Pounds 5bn and Pounds 10bn a year.
Recorded crime statistics showed that direct losses from burglary exceeded
Pounds 1bn.
