<HEADLINE>
FT  05 SEP 94 / Merseyside profit 'declines 18.1%'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The operating profit of Merseyside's top 100 companies, based on accounts
filed in 1993-94, fell 18.1 per cent to Pounds 569m from Pounds 695m as they
fought for business in the recession.
Merseyside plc, an aggregate analysis by accountants KPMG Peat Marwick of
the area's biggest businesses, says the fall in operating profit occurred in
spite of a 3.1 per cent rise in turnover, indicating a significant squeeze
on margins.
This, it says, is likely to be due to companies being unable to pass cost
increases to consumers in full and new business being won at lower margins.
It notes, however, that Pilkington, the glass maker, accounted for 71 per
cent of the operating profits fall.
An increase in non-trading income and reduced interest charges contained the
fall in pre-tax profits - down to Pounds 461m from Pounds 543m - to 15 per
cent.
The businesses on which the analysis is based include plcs and private
companies.
The survey, compiled as a barometer of the area's economic health, says the
pressure on margins has encouraged managements to review productivity,
resulting in enhanced competitiveness and high capital investment.
KPMG says this trend, with Merseyside's recently declared eligibility for
European Union Objective 1 funds, supports the view that the tide is turning
for Merseyside.
It expresses concern that long-term investment in fixed assets is being
financed by short-term borrowing. This and the 20 per cent increase in
long-term loans suggest the need for rights issues or business sales in the
current financial year, it says.
After depreciation, net additions to fixed assets totalled Pounds 661m. The
average number of employees fell more than 6 per cent, while pay rose 4 per
cent.
Interest cover fell to 2.9 times from three and return on capital employed
was down to 7 per cent from 8.6 per cent.
Merseyside plc. KPMG Peat Marwick, Richmond House, 1 Rumford Place,
Liverpool L3 9QY. Free.
